      "description": "\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;font color\u003d\u0026quot;red\u0026quot;\u0026gt;\u0026lt;strong\u0026gt;\u0026gt;\u0026nbsp;TINTIN\u0027S CASE\u0026lt;/strong\u0026gt;\u0026lt;/font\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;blockquote\u0026gt;In 1980, Gerard TOUITOU was an Olivetti computer salesman in Belgium. He built probably the first  portable computer in the world, before Osborne, Kaypro, IBM and others. \u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt; It was a ZX-80 (then later a ZX-81) fitted into a briefcase, along with a printer and a tape recorder. The display was a mini-portable TV set. \u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt; French magazines of the time called it \u0027Tintin\u0027s case\u0027 (as Tintin father, Herg\u0026eacute;, was from Belgium too)\u0026lt;/blockquote\u0026gt;",
